{"schema": {"fields":[{"type":"integer","name":"index"},{"type":"string","name":"author_association"},{"type":"string","name":"body"},{"type":"datetime","name":"created_at"},{"type":"string","name":"html_url"},{"type":"integer","name":"id"},{"type":"string","name":"issue_url"},{"type":"string","name":"node_id"},{"type":"datetime","name":"updated_at"},{"type":"string","name":"url"},{"type":"string","name":"user"}],"pandas_version":"0.20.0","primaryKey":["index"]}, "data": [{"index":0,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"Another note: A `mesh.material`'s opacity would be multiplicative relative to the opacity that the Mesh has relative to it's parent. So if a parent has opacity 0.5, and the child mesh has opacity 0.5, and the child mesh's material has opacity 0.5, then the final opacity of the material when rendered (not including texture's pixel opacities) is 0.5 * 0.5 * 0.5. And obviously, texture pixel opacities would further affect the result.","created_at":"2018-02-26T00:49:16.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/13440#issuecomment-368361693","id":368361693,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/13440","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM2ODM2MTY5Mw==","updated_at":"2018-02-26T00:49:16.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/368361693","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars3.githubusercontent.com\/u\/297678?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/trusktr","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjI5NzY3OA==","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"trusktr","type":"User","id":297678,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/orgs"}},{"index":1,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"### Example use case:\r\n\r\nImagine a large team making a game:\r\n\r\nThere might be a whole team making a few objects characters. They might want to animate the opacity of certain parts of the characters.\r\n\r\nThen there might be another team that takes the characters and makes them move around the world, and might want to fade the character in or out of the scene for whatever reason (f.e. to signify invulnerability with blinking opacity, or maybe a character has become a ghost, etc).\r\n\r\nIf one team tries to traverse the tree and touch all the parts that the other team is touching, then there will be conflicts and unexpected results.\r\n\r\nBetter to solve this once at the engine level. (which is better than making the teams create their own engines on top of an engine). The lower it is abstracted, the more people it will benefit. For example, here in Three.js seems like the best place.","created_at":"2018-02-26T01:04:01.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/13440#issuecomment-368362970","id":368362970,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/13440","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM2ODM2Mjk3MA==","updated_at":"2018-02-26T01:04:34.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/368362970","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars3.githubusercontent.com\/u\/297678?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/trusktr","gists_url":"https:\